Would this be the best way to check which radio button has been selected?
// update the atmosphere effect based on the button clicked
      toggleGroup.selectedToggleProperty().addListener((observable, oldValue, newValue) -> {
        if (noSunButton.isSelected()){
          sceneView.setSunLighting(LightingMode.NO_LIGHT);
        }
        else if (sunOnlyButton.isSelected()){
          sceneView.setSunLighting(LightingMode.LIGHT);
        }
        else if (sunAndShadowsButton.isSelected()){
          sceneView.setSunLighting(LightingMode.LIGHT_AND_SHADOWS);
        }
      });

That would certainly work! A perhaps sleeker way would be to set the 'user data' (it's like a readable property) of the toggle button to be a value of the LightingMode enum, and read that out in the listener. The surface placement placement sample does this, so you could borrow from there:
https://github.com/Esri/arcgis-runtime-samples-java/blob/master/scene/surface-placement/src/main/java/com/esri/samples/surface_placement/SurfacePlacementSample.java#L142-L159
@jenmerritt will be turning surface placement into a sample using fxml, so you could both check if there's a way to set the user data within the fxml or not (I don't actually know!)

I couldn't find a way to set the user data to the LightMode in FXML. However, does this seem correct?
// set the lighting mode of the buttons
noSunButton.setUserData(LightingMode.NO_LIGHT);
sunOnlyButton.setUserData(LightingMode.LIGHT);
sunAndShadowsButton.setUserData(LightingMode.LIGHT_AND_SHADOWS);

// update the atmosphere effect based on the button clicked
toggleGroup.selectedToggleProperty().addListener((observable, oldToggle, newToggle) -> {
	if (toggleGroup.getSelectedToggle() != null)
	  sceneView.setSunLighting((LightingMode) toggleGroup.getSelectedToggle().getUserData());
  });

